%h1
  Engagement services 

%p
  We specialise in getting almost anyone to consider and talk about the health of their minds in a positive way. If you want to encourage a group of people - staff, patients, citizens, customers - to take better care of their minds, or talk more openly about mental health, then we can help.

%p
  All our engagement services begin with the core Mindapples question 
  %i
    "what's the 5-a-day for your mind?"
  This simple opening gives us a positive route into the topic and encourages people to reflect and take notice of what they do already to look after themselves. The question itself also contains important knowledge for individuals about the importance of looking after our minds and the role of our own day-to-day activities in maintaining our mental wellbeing. Once people are engaged in a positive conversation about the health of their minds, we can either pass them on to others to provide services and support, or work with people to help them learn what works for them and build good habits to take care of themselves.
  
%h2
  Digital engagement

%p
  We use digital tools to engage people at scale for low costs and get large numbers of individuals sharing their mindapples and joining the conversation. We invite public contributions to the Mindapples survey through our website www.mindapples.org, and run bespoke surveys and online communities for clients to help large groups of people discuss what works for them and find new activities to try. 

%h2
  Installations and pop-ups

%p
  We support and promote our scalable digital tools through more traditional methods of engagement, using eye-catching installations to start positive conversations and gather 5-a-day suggestions from all kinds of people, in private and at public events. 

%p
  The Mindapples Tree is a unique installation which engages passers-by in sharing their mindapples on specially-designed cards and hanging them on the tree, creating a fascinating display of all the things people are doing to look after their minds. In 2010 the Mindapples Tree was used to engage individuals in a range of contexts including workplaces, cinemas, music festivals, professional conferences and even art galleries. 
  
